30
00:02:10,280 --> 00:02:11,670
You're not listening to me.

31
00:02:11,680 --> 00:02:13,350
Everything always has to be your way.

32
00:02:13,360 --> 00:02:15,120
And what is the one right way?

33
00:02:15,130 --> 00:02:17,510
I mean, how many times
have I told you this?

34
00:02:17,520 --> 00:02:18,520
I thought this was what you wanted.

35
00:02:18,530 --> 00:02:20,550
No, it's obviously what you want.

36
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:22,450
You're just angry that
your book was rejected.

37
00:02:22,460 --> 00:02:24,150
Oh, how dare you bring that up again?

38
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:26,010
You're always at the university!

39
00:02:26,020 --> 00:02:27,820
How about use show some
interest in someone

40
00:02:27,830 --> 00:02:29,910
who didn't die 200 years ago?

41
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:31,729
I don't know how much
longer I can keep this up.

42
00:02:31,730 --> 00:02:33,300
We need to go back to Nigeria.

43
00:02:33,310 --> 00:02:35,530
No, we are not going. My family is here.

44
00:02:35,540 --> 00:02:37,870
And we did this for your career.

45
00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:42,310
Good morning, Chidi.

46
00:02:42,320 --> 00:02:43,510
Would you like some breakfast?

47
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:45,150
I have a presentation.

48
00:02:45,160 --> 00:02:46,290
- Here's a syllabus.

49
00:02:46,300 --> 00:02:48,209
Take one and pass them on.

50
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:51,379
My lecture will take
approximately 55 minutes.

51
00:02:51,380 --> 00:02:53,010
Let's begin, shall we?

52
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:57,390
In conclusion, there
is one clear answer,

53
00:02:57,400 --> 00:03:00,839
and it's that the two of
you should stay married.

54
00:03:00,840 --> 00:03:02,360
Questions?

55
00:03:02,370 --> 00:03:05,600
That was clear

56
00:03:05,620 --> 00:03:07,430
and persuasive,

57
00:03:07,440 --> 00:03:09,520
- and you have made a strong case.
- Yes.

58
00:03:09,530 --> 00:03:12,930
Well argued. Better than
some of my grad students.

59
00:03:12,940 --> 00:03:15,039
You should get ready for
school. I'll take you.

60
00:03:15,040 --> 00:03:16,590
We'll both take you.

61
00:03:18,630 --> 00:03:19,990
It worked?

62
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:21,060
Perfectly.

63
00:03:21,070 --> 00:03:22,582
They're happy again, Uzo.

64
00:03:22,583 --> 00:03:24,490
They're even talking about
getting me a puppy.

65
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:27,490
But more importantly,
I proved once and for all

66
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:29,999
that you can always find the answer.

67
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,560
- The answer to what?
- To anything.

68
00:03:32,570 --> 00:03:34,540
Every problem has an answer.

69
00:03:34,550 --> 00:03:36,700
If you just read enough books
and think hard enough,

70
00:03:36,710 --> 00:03:39,240
you can figure out the
answer to any question.

71
00:03:39,250 --> 00:03:42,139
I know you're really smart,
but that sounds wrong.

72
00:03:42,140 --> 00:03:43,940
Children, please take your seats.

73
00:03:43,950 --> 00:03:45,559
Here's a perfect example.

74
00:03:45,560 --> 00:03:47,970
Where to sit? What's the answer?

75
00:03:47,980 --> 00:03:50,980
Obviously, we want to be
back by the pencil sharpener

76
00:03:50,990 --> 00:03:52,559
but in the front I can see

77
00:03:52,560 --> 00:03:53,819
the blackboard better.

78
00:03:53,820 --> 00:03:57,279
Or by the door to get a nice breeze.

79
00:03:57,280 --> 00:03:58,786
- Chidi.
- Just hang on.

80
00:03:58,787 --> 00:04:00,489
Sorry.

81
00:04:00,490 --> 00:04:02,570
Oh, no.

82
00:04:09,610 --> 00:04:11,170
I still say Professor Lindeman

83
00:04:11,180 --> 00:04:12,990
was a fool to abandon Chidi.

84
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:14,900
He has a brilliant mind.

85
00:04:14,910 --> 00:04:17,680
One day he will use it to solve
the world's biggest problems.

86
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:19,940
Is this enough cheese? I
hope this is enough cheese.

87
00:04:19,950 --> 00:04:21,880
There's sheep, goat, and cow's milk.

88
00:04:21,890 --> 00:04:23,080
- I can run and get more.
- Oh, no.

89
00:04:23,090 --> 00:04:25,059
This is plenty of cheese.

90
00:04:25,060 --> 00:04:29,020
I have to ask, has Chidi
always been so thoughtful?

91
00:04:29,030 --> 00:04:30,590
Ever since he was a child.

92
00:04:30,600 --> 00:04:33,439
I'm sure you've heard about
his first great lecture.

93
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:35,390
Oh, no. Not that old story again.

94
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:37,360
It's so embarrassing.

95
00:04:37,370 --> 00:04:38,620
Oh, go ahead.

96
00:04:38,630 --> 00:04:39,670
A long time ago,

97
00:04:39,680 --> 00:04:42,739
Emeka and I were going
through a rough patch,

98
00:04:42,740 --> 00:04:45,320
and our little Chidi,
at eight years old,

99
00:04:45,330 --> 00:04:47,539
comes in with a one-hour lecture.

100
00:04:47,540 --> 00:04:49,670
All about why we should stay married,

101
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:51,530
and all these years later,

102
00:04:51,540 --> 00:04:53,140
here we still are.

103
00:04:53,150 --> 00:04:55,340
- It's the reason I got into philosophy.
- Mm-hmm.

104
00:04:55,350 --> 00:04:57,400
The biggest questions
and the biggest answers,

105
00:04:57,410 --> 00:04:59,120
you just gotta find them.

106
00:04:59,130 --> 00:05:01,520
I mean, I love philosophy, too,

107
00:05:01,530 --> 00:05:03,840
but I'd argue that, say,
theoretical physics

108
00:05:03,850 --> 00:05:05,880
presents bigger questions
than philosophy.

109
00:05:05,890 --> 00:05:07,480
Oh...

110
00:05:09,540 --> 00:05:10,809
Do you really think that?

111
00:05:10,810 --> 00:05:12,689
Should I switch to physics?

112
00:05:13,710 --> 00:05:18,140
So obviously my parents loved you.

113
00:05:18,150 --> 00:05:19,220
I'm so glad.

114
00:05:19,230 --> 00:05:20,770
They're great.

115
00:05:20,780 --> 00:05:21,989
We have to break up.

116
00:05:21,990 --> 00:05:25,280
Uh, wait. What? Why?

117
00:05:25,290 --> 00:05:27,480
I've been feeling this
way for a while now.

118
00:05:27,490 --> 00:05:30,400
It's just... why are we together?

119
00:05:30,410 --> 00:05:31,980
Because it... it makes sense.

120
00:05:31,990 --> 00:05:34,090
I mean, you like Kant. I like Kant.

121
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:35,289
We're not a book group.

122
00:05:35,290 --> 00:05:38,250
I mean, but we're not not a book group.

123
00:05:38,260 --> 00:05:41,820
Okay, if there's a problem
with our relationship,

124
00:05:41,830 --> 00:05:43,960
there is an answer that will solve it.

125
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:46,640
- So, let's hit the library.
- You wanna use philosophy?

126
00:05:46,650 --> 00:05:47,849
How about David Hume?

127
00:05:47,850 --> 00:05:50,140
"Reason is and ought only to be

128
00:05:50,150 --> 00:05:51,809
a slave to the passions."

129
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:55,479
You know, emotions, desires, feelings.

130
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:58,430
- Do you have any of those?
- Of course I have feelings.

131
00:05:58,440 --> 00:06:00,989
I... I have strong
feelings for... for you

132
00:06:00,990 --> 00:06:02,730
and... and what we have,

133
00:06:02,740 --> 00:06:07,280
and right now, I will show you...

134
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,249
How Kant refuted most of
Hume's central theses.

135
00:06:14,250 --> 00:06:15,499
- Oh, my God.
- He...

136
00:06:26,050 --> 00:06:27,580
So, what do you think?

137
00:06:27,590 --> 00:06:30,519
I think it's 3,600 pages.

138
00:06:30,520 --> 00:06:33,090
I have a job, Chidi. I have a family.

139
00:06:33,100 --> 00:06:35,769
Until I had to read this,
I had a will to live.

140
00:06:35,770 --> 00:06:40,580
This work is an insane,
tangled web of inscrutability.

141
00:06:40,590 --> 00:06:42,540
In the fun,

142
00:06:42,550 --> 00:06:45,409
"grad students will analyze
this for centuries" way?

143
00:06:45,410 --> 00:06:46,909
No, in the Unabomber way.

144
00:06:46,910 --> 00:06:50,160
Okay, well, um, I'll write
my way out of the maze.

145
00:06:50,170 --> 00:06:51,830
I'll re-outline the middle chapters,

146
00:06:51,840 --> 00:06:53,249
- do more research...
- No, Chidi.

147
00:06:53,250 --> 00:06:55,470
You can't answer every question

148
00:06:55,480 --> 00:06:57,020
every philosopher has ever asked,

149
00:06:57,030 --> 00:07:00,750
so what in these pages
do you care about?

150
00:07:00,760 --> 00:07:02,990
- All of it. Equally.
- Shut up.

151
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:04,340
- But...
- Shut up, shut up.

152
00:07:04,350 --> 00:07:07,500
- Should I...
- Shut up, shut up.

153
00:07:07,510 --> 00:07:11,920
The greatest works of modern
philosophy are emotional.

154
00:07:11,930 --> 00:07:16,650
They make an argument about
how the world is and ought to be.

155
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:20,109
There is a great mind at work in here,

156
00:07:20,110 --> 00:07:22,160
but where is the heart?

157
00:07:22,170 --> 00:07:23,930
Where are the guts?

158
00:07:23,940 --> 00:07:26,630
I understand. I do.

159
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:32,289
So I'm going to go home and
compose a short paper for you,

160
00:07:32,290 --> 00:07:35,570
arguing that I should continue
working on this longer paper.

161
00:07:35,580 --> 00:07:37,000
Shut up!

162
00:07:40,120 --> 00:07:42,200
Wow, tough week.

163
00:07:42,210 --> 00:07:43,420
Sorry, pal.

164
00:07:44,420 --> 00:07:46,219
I mean, honestly, I don't
know what hurts more;

165
00:07:46,220 --> 00:07:48,670
my thesis meeting or Allesandra.

166
00:07:48,680 --> 00:07:51,920
She was brilliant and... and funny.

167
00:07:51,930 --> 00:07:55,960
I thought that maybe she was the answer.

168
00:07:55,970 --> 00:07:59,230
Some things in life
don't have an answer.

169
00:07:59,240 --> 00:08:01,360
Isn't that what Allesandra was saying?

170
00:08:01,370 --> 00:08:04,100
Isn't that what your advisor said, too?

171
00:08:04,110 --> 00:08:06,040
Isn't that what everyone who
knows you has said to you

172
00:08:06,050 --> 00:08:07,600
at every waking moment of your life?

173
00:08:07,610 --> 00:08:10,500
Okay, I can figure this out.
I just need to find the answer

174
00:08:10,510 --> 00:08:12,400
for how to impress Allesandra,

175
00:08:12,410 --> 00:08:15,000
a separate answer for how
to impress my advisor,

176
00:08:15,010 --> 00:08:18,499
or ideally, one answer for
how to impress them both.

177
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:19,740
Oh, you know what this calls for.

178
00:08:19,750 --> 00:08:21,230
- Don't say it.
- A Venn diagram.

179
00:08:21,240 --> 00:08:22,790
No Venn diagram.

180
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:25,020
If you won't listen to other people,

181
00:08:25,030 --> 00:08:26,919
do you at least hear what you're saying?

182
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:29,469
I swear, sometimes it
is literally impossible

183
00:08:29,470 --> 00:08:30,479
to be your friend.

184
00:08:30,480 --> 00:08:32,440
You're incapable of
making a single decision.

185
00:08:32,450 --> 00:08:34,710
Look, what's the harm in
taking a few extra minutes

186
00:08:34,720 --> 00:08:36,099
to find the perfect...

187
00:08:42,730 --> 00:08:44,610
Chidi, come on in.

188
00:08:45,390 --> 00:08:47,520
Unless you'd be more
comfortable out here.

189
00:08:47,530 --> 00:08:51,720
Oh, well, I feel like you want me to...

190
00:08:51,730 --> 00:08:53,350
I tell you what. I'll decide for you.

191
00:08:53,360 --> 00:08:55,010
- Come on in.
- Great.

192
00:09:01,090 --> 00:09:02,879
Watch this.

193
00:09:02,880 --> 00:09:05,920
Your fridge chooses
your breakfast for you.

194
00:09:05,930 --> 00:09:07,820
Oatmeal and almond milk.

195
00:09:07,830 --> 00:09:10,200
Extra filmy. You don't
even have to decide.

196
00:09:10,210 --> 00:09:11,630
It just knows what you want,

197
00:09:11,640 --> 00:09:13,800
and for all your other requests,

198
00:09:13,810 --> 00:09:15,599
Janet?

199
00:09:15,600 --> 00:09:16,880
Hi there.

200
00:09:16,890 --> 00:09:19,120
Janet knows the answers

201
00:09:19,130 --> 00:09:21,580
to all the questions in the universe.

202
00:09:21,590 --> 00:09:22,689
Ask her anything.

203
00:09:22,690 --> 00:09:25,440
I mean, which answer do I want?

204
00:09:25,450 --> 00:09:27,800
I mean, something profound, obviously.

205
00:09:27,810 --> 00:09:29,909
It shouldn't be trivial or salacious.

206
00:09:29,910 --> 00:09:33,329
Or maybe I should start
small and maybe ramp up.

207
00:09:33,330 --> 00:09:36,440
Or... I can't...

208
00:09:36,450 --> 00:09:38,700
- What's the biggest fish?
- The whale shark.

209
00:09:38,710 --> 00:09:39,880
Cool.

210
00:09:40,620 --> 00:09:42,520
I'm sorry. I'll have
better questions later.

211
00:09:42,530 --> 00:09:44,380
You don't need to apologize, Chidi.

212
00:09:44,390 --> 00:09:46,780
All questions are equally
important to me.

213
00:09:46,790 --> 00:09:49,179
Oh, well then you and I
are gonna get along great.

214
00:09:51,190 --> 00:09:53,320
I need to go welcome
some more residents.

215
00:09:53,330 --> 00:09:56,260
Are there any other questions
I can answer for you before I go?

216
00:09:56,270 --> 00:09:59,899
Well, yes. Is... is there
a relationship equivalent

217
00:09:59,900 --> 00:10:01,830
to the oatmeal?

218
00:10:01,840 --> 00:10:04,649
Uh, is there, like, a sort of...

219
00:10:04,650 --> 00:10:07,279
Soul mate? Yes.

220
00:10:07,280 --> 00:10:11,770
Every person in the Good
Place has one perfect match.

221
00:10:11,780 --> 00:10:14,000
In an hour, come on by the little house

222
00:10:14,010 --> 00:10:15,240
that looks like a face

223
00:10:15,250 --> 00:10:18,369
and get the answer to
your ultimate question.

224
00:10:18,370 --> 00:10:20,292
Her name's Eleanor.

225
00:10:28,680 --> 00:10:32,710
Oh, man. Remember this?

226
00:10:32,720 --> 00:10:33,800
Yeah, yeah.

227
00:10:33,810 --> 00:10:35,890
- It was eight minutes ago.
- Mm-hmm.

228
00:10:35,900 --> 00:10:39,840
So you just proposed to
Janet, and you said yes.

229
00:10:39,850 --> 00:10:40,890
- And now you're married.
- Mm-hmm.

230
00:10:40,900 --> 00:10:42,920
You know, I thought saying that out loud

231
00:10:42,930 --> 00:10:45,810
would make it less
insane, but it did not.

232
00:10:45,820 --> 00:10:46,900
Thanks, homie.

233
00:10:46,910 --> 00:10:48,340
If you'd like to get us a present,

234
00:10:48,350 --> 00:10:50,529
we're registered at me.

235
00:10:50,530 --> 00:10:53,150
Jason, I think I need your help.

236
00:10:53,160 --> 00:10:54,440
- Can I ask you something?
- Cool.

237
00:10:54,450 --> 00:10:56,280
No one's ever asked
me for advice before,

238
00:10:56,290 --> 00:10:57,869
and you're a high school principal.

239
00:10:57,870 --> 00:10:59,000
College professor.

240
00:10:59,010 --> 00:11:01,289
Who... who told you how to do this?

241
00:11:01,290 --> 00:11:04,379
Like, how can you just
make a decision this big?

242
00:11:04,380 --> 00:11:07,870
Chidi, here's the thing with stuff.

243
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:10,150
You can look at a problem
from every angle

244
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:12,260
and drive yourself crazy, but sometimes,

245
00:11:12,270 --> 00:11:14,900
you just gotta huck a
Molotov cocktail at a drone

246
00:11:14,910 --> 00:11:16,679
and see what happens.

247
00:11:16,680 --> 00:11:18,470
Is what happens that the drone blows up?

248
00:11:18,480 --> 00:11:20,400
Usually. I mean, where I'm from,

249
00:11:20,410 --> 00:11:21,970
most things blow up eventually,

250
00:11:21,980 --> 00:11:24,220
so I learned that when
something dope comes along,

251
00:11:24,230 --> 00:11:25,890
you gotta lock it down.

252
00:11:25,900 --> 00:11:28,320
If you're always frozen in
fear and taking too long

253
00:11:28,330 --> 00:11:29,740
to think about what to do,

254
00:11:29,750 --> 00:11:31,720
you'll miss your opportunity
and maybe get sucked

255
00:11:31,730 --> 00:11:33,654
into the propeller of a swamp boat.

256
00:11:33,655 --> 00:11:35,390
I just... I don't think I'll ever be

257
00:11:35,400 --> 00:11:38,539
the kind of person who just acts.

258
00:11:38,540 --> 00:11:42,390
I mean, I can't just open
a door and walk through

